It is a structural design pattern.
It organizes objects into tree structures, enabling clients to treat
 individual and composite objects uniforly through a common interface.
Simplifies code and supports easy extension without modifying client logic. 

Explanation:
We have a FILESYSTEM---1.Folders ----1.1 Folders
                       2.Files       1.2 Files
Its a tree structure
File is similar to leaf node and folder is similar to composite nodes.     

class FILE-- name, size(), open()[It is a method which gives content of file when method is called. ]

class FOLDER-- name, vector<Files>files, vector<Folder>folders
**FOLDER can have 1-to-many Files and can also have 1-to-many folders.

Now we use some commands like;-
ls()--list directory --lists all the files and folders present in a root folder.
Ex : ROOT--1.file1.txt
          2.file2.txt
          3.folder
          4.file3.txt

openAll() -- expands the hierarchy   
if call openAll on FILE -- cout<<FILENAME  
if call openAll on FOLDER:
 it will first go through vector<Files>files and cout << FILENAME and then goes through vector<Folder>folders and again in that folder if we have files cout << FILENAME and then go to folders and checks and same loop.
 So output for the ROOT FOLDER would be --1.file1.txt
                                          2.file2.txt
                                          3.file3.txt
                                          4.folder

The order gets disrupted. To maintain order instead of seperate lists for files and folder we need to maintain same list for both files and folders.

Considering a common list for both files and folders, vector<>CommonList;
Now, calling method openAll():
 first will check the type of the element in List:
  for(){
    if(ele==file){
     cout<<FILENAME
    }else{
      ele->openAll()    i.e if it is folder will again call openAll() for the elements present inside the folder.
    }
  }

  This is all mess using much more methods like this.
  So we use COMPOSITE DESIGN PATTERN, which says we need to treat Composite and leaf nodes in same way that means they should have a common interface/class/abstract class
  So that these will override the methods in common interface according to them. 
  The adv is no if-else conditions has to be managed. etc

Applications;
File systems, represneting files, directories and hierarchical relationships.

Components:
1.COMPONENT: It is the common interface for all objects in the compostion. It defines the methods that are common to both leaf and composite objects.
2.LEAF: Object that doesnt have any children
COMPOSITE: Container object that has leaf objects and Composite objects.
CLIENT:Client is responsible for using component interface to work with objects in the composition. Treats leaf and composite objects uniformly.


Working:
The client interacts with objects through common Component interface.
Leaf objects perform actual work while composite objects store and manage child components.
When an operation is called on a composite, it forwards the request to its children recursively.